content.text:
However, governance gaps have emerged in the implementation of this plan, including:
Fragmented leadership and weak institutional coordination, with ministries and agencies working in silos;
Conflicting policies that undermine long-term transition goals;
Limited public participation and transparency, with minimal influence from local communities, civil society, and marginalized groups;
Weak regulatory oversight, allowing vested economic and political interests to shape energy decisions with limited accountability.
To understand these challenges more systematically, the UNDP applied a conceptual governance framework to assess Nigeria’s energy transition. Before diving into the specific governance issues, we first explore the elements of this framework.
